The Johannesburg Emergency Medical Services (EMS) has called on drivers and residents to be vigilant on the roads following heavy rain. EMS Spokesperson, Robert Mulaudzi says the roads are wet and slippery, which could lead to serious accidents. Gauteng Today ‘s Weather overview: 10.4.2022 pic.twitter.com/wFNM3fsGM6 — SA Weather Service (@SAWeatherServic) April 10, 2022  SA Weather | Sunday 10 April 2022 | Mulaudzi has also urged residents to be extra careful with heating appliances when trying to warm themselves up at home. “We are concerned about the extreme cold temperatures. We would like to encourage our residents as they try to warm themselves. Continue to look after all heating devices like imbawula, heaters, candles and paraffin stoves not to leave them unattended. So that we can be able to prevent fire incidents.”